The triumph of right-wing populists in Austria, together they have 29 percent
According to early preliminary results, Sunday's early parliamentary elections in Austria have resulted in a marked weakening of both sides of the current grand coalition and a significant strengthening of right-wing populist parties.
The Austrian People's Party (ÖVP) has suffered particularly heavy losses, with the position of current President Wilhelm Molterer seriously shaking.
On the contrary, the electoral leader of the Union for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), Carinthian Governor Jörg Haider, is preparing a triumphant return to national politics.
According to preliminary results, it remains the strongest party in the country of social democracy (SPÖ) with 29.8 percent of the vote, but loses 5.5 percent of the vote compared to the last election in 2006.
Even worse was the ÖVP, which is losing almost nine percent of the vote with 25.6 percent.
These are the worst results of both these major parties in Austria's post-war history, and a disastrous result, especially for the People's Party, which triggered early elections.
As early as early July, when the ÖVP left the coalition, the People's Party had a significant lead over the SPÖ in preferences.
But voters apparently punished them for letting the government fail.
Speculation about the possible resignation of the party chairman and current vice-chancellor Wilhelm Molterer was already in the first reaction to the results.
Observers believe this could happen as early as Monday at an extraordinary meeting of the party's bureau.
Such a development would probably make it easier to get to the most likely outcome of the election result, which is to renew the grand coalition between the SPÖ and the ÖVP.
But, with the two right-wing populist parties strengthening - the Frees (FPÖ) gained a provisional 18 percent and the BZÖ 11 percent of the vote - the Social Democrats also expressed concern about a repeat of 1999, when the People's Party agreed with the populists (the FPÖ was still united then, split from the BZÖ in 2005) on a joint government that even triggered sanctions by the European Union.
Haider, who has already stated that he is ready to work with any party and envisages a return to Vienna for national politics, is clearly betting on this development.
The Green Party also entered parliament, but lost slightly and fell from third to fifth place among Austrian political parties.
Apparently, none of the other parties over 4% have crossed the threshold and have not made it to parliament.
Knife-edge duel: MP3 players against mobiles.
We will advise you on how to choose
While almost every mobile can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can make a phone call.
From this it seems clear that it is better to buy only a phone.
Still, there are enough reasons to get a standalone player.
The choice depends entirely on the method of use and the claims of the future owner.
It's probably hard to get a high-end, expensive record player home to listen to Maxim Turbulenc's latest album.
On the one hand, such music products do not come out on LP records and from a qualitative point of view there is no objective reason for this.
However, if vinyl with art rock, jazz or blues is on your shelves, you will probably at least dream of such a record player.
It is the same with music on the go, i.e. music compressed, simplified - music in MP3.
Here, too, there are price and quality categories.
It may be unacceptable for some to spend 8,000 crowns on a player, just as a Pink Floyd fan will have a hard time biting a 20-crown headphone from the market.
Two extremes, between which there is enough space for everyone.
The selection is wide.
Battery life also determines
Some high-end music players can do much more than just play music, but what most mobiles can't do at all.
No current device is as versatile as a phone.
In addition to primary functions, telephony and texting, he can play music and video, record both, have a better, worse camera and even navigate.
And considering smartphones and communicators, you'll have a small computer in your pocket.
It's a little miracle, because no fridge can grill and no TV can take pictures.
The versatility of the mobile also brings disadvantages.
The more features you use on your mobile, the sooner the indicator on the display will send you to the charger.
And playing music is one of the biggest energy eaters.
Few mobiles can play music for more than ten or twelve hours, most of them much less.
In this respect, music players (especially the simplest ones) are significantly more powerful.
For cheap mobiles, be aware that they won't play for more than a few hours.
If you call again and there, get another charger to work just in case - this also applies to more expensive devices.
With MP3 players, you won't have this problem, even the worse ones last at least 9 hours of continuous operation on a single charge.
Another problem occurs when recording music to mobile.
Unfortunately, only a limited part of the devices has a universal USB connector, and not every one of them can be directly connected to the computer without special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly on a memory card, but few card readers can handle the miniature memory cards used in mobiles without reduction.
With players with exceptions (iPod), you don't need any special software.
Just fill the device with USB music from your computer.
Most mobiles and players already create a music library sorted by artist name, album title, genre or user rating.
Some devices display only the directory tree structure similar to Windows Explorer, and some can do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with the operating system).
Players are easier to operate, mobiles can do more
When choosing a specific device, be especially interested in battery life, memory capacity, quality and type of audio output and, of course, the comfort of operation.
If music is primarily a backdrop for you and if you listen to it every day only briefly on a tram, you only need any mobile that plays MP3.
Which almost any cell phone can do.
You don't even have to watch too much what music formats your mobile or player can do.
MP3 can handle everyone, and the vast majority of music that gets to you will be in this format.
It is one of the most widely used and in addition to it, the vast majority of devices can also handle WMA music.
Less AAC (the format used by Apple and its iPods) occurs less.
Better mobiles also allow, for example, the purchase of music online.
Just visit the relevant website of the operator (or another provider) via the mobile internet and buy a song or album.
This service alone could be a strong argument for acquiring a music mobile.
Unfortunately, the offer of operators is lousy and is mostly limited to fast-fermented radio hits.
Prices are also not the lowest.
However, it is generally assumed that this way of selling music (whether via GSM, the Internet or wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people carry their cell phones around all the time.
Whenever you feel like listening to something, you can feel the phone in your pocket, while the MP3 player lies forgotten at home.
However, it still depends on whether you always carry headphones or at least wired hands-free.
If not, you can take advantage of the integrated speaker that almost every mobile has, but only a minimum of MP3 players.
Perhaps the biggest advantage of music mobiles will be the price for many.
The cheapest ones normally cost under three thousand.
For three and four thousand crowns you will already get a very decent Walkman.
However, you will usually be limited by the absence of output on regular headphones.
The best and most technically equipped phones with a 3.5 mm socket for regular headphones cost up to fifteen thousand.
The advantage of the players is, among other things, easy operation.
The simplest - not necessarily the cheapest (see our selection) - the players can be controlled by anyone.
The minimum of functions, the similarity of control with a previously common tape recorder or a turntable is obvious.
There is no risk of collision in the form of a mistakenly turned on mobile internet and then a huge bill for data transmission.
What device to reach for
Even the cheapest mobiles (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for interchangeable memory cards (type M2, microSD, etc.).
Even with the purchase of the relevant card, you can fit up to two thousand crowns.
But beware.
For basic models, only cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB are supported.
Only the most expensive can handle even 8 GB of memory devices.
If you already have a mobile and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, reach for Coron, Creativ, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you do not have to spend more than 1,100 CROWNS.
If you are one of the more demanding listeners, you better reach for specialized mobiles - walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some Nokias and Samsungs).
These devices have separate control buttons for MP3 and the operator's comfort is thus close to a separate MP3 player.
The furthest is in the Sony Ericsson industry, whose walkman mobiles have the same user interface as separately sold MP3 players.
The same service and in the same price category up to four thousand crowns, but with more memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (normally 15 hours, up to a maximum of 35 hours), will take mp3 players away from the above brands.
The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic already this year.
maybe
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite mature and our operators offer virtually all services as their partners in Western Europe.
Yet we are missing something here - a virtual operator that would make the classic ones cheaper.
Maybe he won't be missing long.
We have written many times about the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive Mobil.cz the world.
This was confirmed by the CTO, which pointed out that the price of SMS is higher in our country than in the rest of the Union.
After the latest steps of the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming charges, a paradoxical situation may occur - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are holding so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that really wants to fight.
It may sound paradoxical, we have three mobile networks and penetration well over 100%.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, like to play on the fact that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
Pavel Dvořák, president of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (CTU), often invites them to do this, who has stated several times in the past that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is probably true that a classic operator with its own network probably doesn't have much of a chance anymore (after all, it would probably be difficult to find frequencies anymore).
But there is another option - a virtual operator.
It was the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that brought about a significant reduction in prices, to which even classic operators had to respond.
Even before the entry of pikes such as Tesco Mobile and Virgin Mobile into the market, there were similar voices in the UK as in our country.
However, it turned out that the place for such operators is and can be really successful.
After all, we don't have to go too far for examples.
In February this year, we informed you about the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just six months, this operator managed to gain more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator there.
Mobilking is behind the Penta Financial Group, which owns, among others, U:fona in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more specific target group.
They only need far fewer customers than a conventional operator to function efficiently.
They do not entail relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
In the world, virtual operators are usually profiled as low-cost - they offer cheap calls and SMS, but this is often outweighed by a narrower range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half as cheaply as its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, betting on a novel target group can also be a pretty good move.
This operator focuses specifically on men.
"The right guys choose Mobilking - an operator they like and trust," says David Seibertz CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which operates the virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept as in Poland could be caught in our country.
Miroslav Čepický, a spokesman for Vodafone, doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for the segment approach on which most virtual operators are based.
Moreover, it is relatively saturated in terms of service offerings."
No chance in the Czech Republic, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual mobile operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not look very promising.
Rather, Mobilking will be launched in other countries in our region," Jana Studničková, spokeswoman for the Penta Financial Group, said in Mobil.cz interview with The Czech Republic.
Indirectly, it confirmed that existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not in favour of this idea.
On the contrary, it tries to do everything to ensure that no potential competitor arises.
Gts Novera group has been interested in launching a virtual mobile operator for some time, so it would like to take the next step towards becoming a real competitor of O2 Telefónica in the field of corporate customers.
"We are very interested in offering our customers not only fixed but also mobile telecommunication services.
And the sooner the better.
We have repeatedly discussed this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
We have already made progress with some of them in the negotiations," says Pavel Kaidl, the group's spokesman.
Maybe it's a good time, then.
From unofficial information, it seems that we should be looking forward to the first virtual operator perhaps by the end of the year.
For now, however, its creation is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At the moment, we do not believe that there is room on the Czech market for the creation of a full-fledged virtual operator.
The Czech market is very specific compared to other markets.
So far, we have not been approached by any entity with a comprehensive and serious project in this area," vlastimil Sršeň from the press department of Telefónika O2 said in a statement to Mobil.cz.
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
Martina Kemrová, a spokeswoman for T-Mobile, adds in rare agreement with the O2 statement: "So far, we have not seen any viable and mutually beneficial business project on which to continue to build."
He adds: "It is difficult to find a virtual operator in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
At this point, we would have to have a concrete agreement on the table in order to think in this short term."
Vodafone is focusing its attention more on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický says: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, especially in the area of cost and infrastructure sharing.
This is what we consider most profitable from the point of view of our customers.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for fast mobile internet."
Responsible authorities - one hand with operators
The progress of mobile operators is easy to understand, the entry of another operator would mean increased competition, would lead to a decrease in prices and thus a decrease in their profits.
So why make it easier for such a competitor to take over?
The tug-of-shreed of the U:5n formation also proves that when operators are up to something, they can pull together.
Probably the greatest pressure towards the CTO went at the time of the creation of U:fona from T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly available information from the CTO website.
Now, however, U:fon is a good argument for not admiving a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová commented: "Moreover, the competitive environment of the mobile market has recently been enhanced by the entry of a fourth mobile operator into the market.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that the entry of another player would place high demands on him and especially on his services."
However, due to this approach of mobile operators, it is striking that czech regulators are completely uninterested.
This is not just the position of the CTO, which unfortunately does not have the power to intervene in competition in the Czech Republic - unlike the UK and other developed countries.
These belong exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Competition (ÚOHS).
But he took a typical stance on the whole issue.
"Entry of the virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible after a contract has been concluded between the mobile operator and the virtual operator for the lease of the necessary infrastructure.
No such contract has been concluded yet, as the offer of potential bidders was probably not interesting enough for classical operators," kristián Chalupa from the Department of External Relations of the Office of External Relations said in response to our inquiry.
It is perhaps not surprising from the representatives of the operators that this worded statement.
This is more than a consideration from the Authority, which is supposed to represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, to ensure that no one abuses their position on the market.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "In countries where virtual operators normally operate, we can see that their entry into the market has contributed to a decrease in prices for mobile telephone services."
However, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the fall in prices are not among the interests of the IOC.
In fact, what is shocking about the whole case is the touching resemplification of the three mobile operators that result from their reactions.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence is entirely self-asked.
Like the exact same price of petrol at petrol stations, it is certainly only the result of chance and fierce competition.
"The Office has found no evidence of anti-compete behaviour in this matter and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position and therefore does not have adequate increased responsibility for their market behaviour.
The necessary tools for opening up the mobile market for virtual operators are probably also missing from the telecommunications regulator," Chalupa said in a statement.
The interpretation of market dominance is one of many points of contention.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets prepared by the CTO, according to which telecommunications are the only market from the point of view of competition.
Of course, none of the Czech operators have a dominant position on such a market.
However, some legal experts offer a different view - the network operator's consent is always required to create a virtual operator.
And the mobile operator - quite logically - has a monopoly on its network.
So in a certain segment they necessarily have to be dominant.
However, even if we do not accept this argument, it should be at least a warning to the IOC that the three mobile operators are following a strikingly similar approach.
At the same time, complaints from a number of interested parties (including GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles when dealing with all operators.
Blaming the CTO for responsibility is a fairly common trick in telecommunications, which the IOC gives away from the matter.
We've met him on several similar occasions.
Unfortunately, until the recently adopted amendment to the Telecommunications Act, the extension of the CTO's powers to the field of competition in telecommunications failed to be enforced, even though many experts promised to improve the situation.
The IOC representatives need to know this more than well, but apparently their interests are elsewhere.
It's possible when no one's watching
At the same time, the functioning of some pseudo-virtual operators, of which there are several in Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies that issue their own mobile phone price listings, but they are only partially public.
These are usually multilevel marketing companies.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile telephone services.
The price list of these companies usually only reaches the chosen ones.
The magic lies in the fact that the company acts as a classic corporate customer to the operator, ordering a large number of SIM cards.
As a significant customer, he will then receive special price (and other) offers.
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
"If there are cases that you are talking about, it could be a breach of the terms and conditions that we would deal with and could result in termination of cooperation with the company," Martina Kemrová replied to our inquiry on this issue.
However, it is quite unlikely that such activity will not reach the responsible people from mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three mentioned companies, it can be thousands of customers.
None of the operators opposes such a procedure.
They make significant profits from the activities of these companies, and yet - unlike real virtual operators - they do not threaten them with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický points out possible problems: "The law allows such speculation, however, only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
In addition, they must accept that the SIM card on their phone is not in their name, so they cannot have it fully as regular customers of mobile operators."
But that should be strange to say the least.
In addition, another question is opened for the IOC.
If mobile operators are eyeing a similar procedure, why are they blocking the emergence of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the IOC has quite strong powers to detect such activity and, if it does not wish, may not be satisfied with the operators' explanation that they have no idea about this and their terms and conditions prohibit it.
When we won't be the most expensive
As has already been mentioned several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has brought a noticeable decrease in prices for services.
In virtually all countries where virtual operators were created, classic operators tried to prevent their creation more or less.
The arguments they used were virtually identical - too small, possibly too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
But it is at these moments that regulators intervened in developed countries, defending not the interests of mobile operators, but their customers.
Whether through formal measures or informal pressure, they achieved the first virtual operator and packed others on it.
Unfortunately, Czech regulators are tossing the case around like a hot potato.
In our experience, we cannot shake the impression that the lack of competence is more than appropriate in these cases.
But let's not throw a gun in the rye.
If the behind-the-scenes information is correct and the virtual operator will appear with us really soon, the Czech mobile market may be moving again.
If one of the operators has admitted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, it will be difficult for the IOC to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And maybe we'll stop calling more expensive than the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best one
Listen to four performances of the new version of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek inaugurated new recordings of the national anthem Where My Home is on the occasion of The Day of Czech Statehood.
The anthem was newly recorded by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions - with male or female solo vocals, in choral version and instrumental version.
Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka took over the singing.
The anthem adaptations were written by Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
You can listen iHNed.cz four versions on the server on the server.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech national song to be one of the most beautiful hymens.
He has previously told Czech Radio that he deliberately chose singers with young representative voices, which are distinctive and popular, to sing solo variants.
"From the beginning, I tried to make sure that they had clear diction in both of them, and then that they were well understood, that they recircupied," he said.
The Czech national anthem will celebrate its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Where My Home was first performed in 1834 on the boards of the Estates Theatre in josef Kajetán Tyl's original Czech play Fidlovačka, accompanied by music by František Škroup.
It gained popularity, and people spontaneously took it as their own.
The first song was released after the establishment of Czechoslovakia in 1918 and became a natural part of the national anthem.
It remained one of the seven state symbols even after the creation of an independent Czech Republic.
