Even rats have feelings
When a rat or a cockroach flees danger, does that mean they also feel fear?
Neurologist Joseph LeDoux believes that many animals have feelings.
But how could it be verified that they feel the same way when they behave similarly to us?
The internet magazine "Edge" has been publishing contributions from well-known scientists for several years.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents selected answers to the question "What do you consider true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have feelings and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else being able to prove it so far, when we can't even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case, we can at least hope, because all human brains have the same basic configuration.
However, as soon as we start to engage in another species and open up questions of perception or general consciousness, we enter immeasory terrain because the hardware does not match.
When a rat gets into danger, it will do the same thing as many other animals: it will pretend to be dead, flee or attack.
People behave similarly, from which some scientists conclude comparable subjective experiences.
I don't believe in that, though.
Two aspects of the brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to the experience of animals.
This is partly because circuits associated with human consciousness almost always include the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its contribution to short-term memory and performance or control functions).
This vast area is significantly more developed in humans than in other primates, and seems to be completely absent from other creatures.
At least for those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, among them knowing who we are and the ability to plan and make decisions, there is reason to believe that man is even different from other primates.
Another dramatic peculiarity could hide the linguistic nature of a person: since so much of his perception is associated with language, it is often said that consciousness depends on him.
In this case, we could exclude the animals.
But even if consciousness did not matter to the tongue, it would certainly be influenced by language, so that animal consciousness, however constructed it may be, would probably differ from most states of our consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to know what consciousness looks like in other animals.
When, as something internal and subjective, it is not even possible to measure, due to special hardware, to analyze it on the basis of our own experience, it puts us in great trouble to explore it.
Most of my outlets relate to the content of conscious experience, but there is another aspect of consciousness that should be more scientifically accessible.
It would be possible to examine processes in the consciousness of animals regardless of their content, and this is exactly what happens in short-term memory studies in primates, especially in the example of visualization.
But this approach, pursued by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, focuses on the neural correlates of consciousness rather than causal mechanisms: both may be identical, but they may not be.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasizes the importance of non-confrontational cortex for the realization of visualization.
What does that mean for feelings?
I infer them from the fact that an emotional system, such as the fear system, is activated in a brain conscious of its own activity.
So what we refer to as "fear" is the mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of a defense system located in the brain (or its consequences, such as bodily responses) uses memory.
Seen from this angle, feelings are closely intertwined with those areas of the cortex that are characterized by primates, and especially humans.
In connection with linguistic nature, a subtle gradation of perception arises, because we can use words and grammar to distinguish and categorize states so that we can attribute them side by side to others.
Antonio Damasio, for example, believes that feelings arise from more primitive activities in cortex and brain stem areas devoted to bodily sensations, similar to Jaak Pankseep, who focuses more on the brain stem.
Since this network has not changed much in the course of human evolution, it could easily participate in the feelings perceived by multiple animal genera.
In theory, I cannot oppose this, but I find it inconclusive.
Pankseep argues that what seems to us to be fear in rats and humans probably feel the same way: But how can it be verified, Pankseep goes on to say, whether rats and humans feel the same way when they behave similarly?
The cockroach flees from danger - does he also feel fear?
From my point of view, the mere similarity of behavior cannot prove the conformity of experience.
It is true that the neural comparison takes us further: rats and humans have similar brain stems, on the other hand, cockroaches and brains.
But is the brain stem responsible for the feelings?
And even if it could be proved in humans: how would we want to prove it in rats?
I believe that rats and other mammals, perhaps even cockroaches (who knows?), have feelings.
But I really don't know how to prove it.
And since their feelings are probably fundamentally different from ours (because human consciousness rests on special circuits and language), I examine emotional behavior rather than emotional perception of rats.
In any case, we can expect progress at the neural level if we measure the same in rats and humans.
As with rats, I don't check my tongue and consciousness, I don't even look at feelings, I don't know if they exist.
It may be considered shortsighted, but I prefer to move forward rather than throw myself against the wall repeatedly.
I'm a practical emotionalist.
