Dark matter affects space probe flight
For years, scientists have been unaware of one mysterious phenomenon: dark matter affects the speed of space probes during the so-called swing-by maneuver.
Experts fear that Albert Einstein's general theory of relativity might not be entirely correct.
For almost 18 years, the space probe "Ulysses" has been flying through space.
Fuel lines, which will soon freeze, now threaten to die of winter.
For years, a mysterious phenomenon has been causing confusion among scientists - the anomaly of a gravitational slingshot.
A gravitational slingshot is an aerial maneuver of space probes in which they gain additional momentum in the gravitational field of a space body, such as Earth.
Thanks to this, the probes can save a lot of fuel.
The European-American cassini-huygens research probe used this physical trick as well as the Ulysses solar probe.
But what scientists have been saying for years in this case is astonishing: flying bodies do not behave 100% as one would expect under the good old law of gravity.
On the contrary, there are irregularities in speed.
Probes are unexpectedly accelerating or slowing down.
So far, physicists have failed to explain this effect.
He was baptized by the anomalies of the gravitational slingshot.
Several experts fear that even Albert Einstein's general theory of relativity, which describes the attraction of matter by curvature of space, might not be entirely correct.
American physicist Stephen Adler of the Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton remains convinced that Einstein was right, and is trying to explain the anomaly of the gravitational slingshot using so-called dark matter, the presence of which in the universe has been detected by astronomers.
"Dark matter could be responsible for this anomaly, which could also be very close to Earth," he writes.
Space researchers have only known about the existence of dark matter for about ten years.
It is clearly based on a gravitational force, the effect of which on other space bodies can be observed.
On the contrary, it itself is completely invisible, which means that it does not emit or reflect any electromagnetic radiation, not even visible light.
According to the calculations of scientists, this dark matter is a good fifth of the total mass of the universe.
