Turkey's diplomatic horizons widening
Long before Turkey began to seek to join the European Union, European powers longed to penetrate deep into Turkey's borders.
On the east bank of the Bosphorus, perhaps just twenty paces in Asia, stands one of the finest monuments of this failed imperial ambition.
Hydarpaša railway station was designed by two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Con in the Neo-Renaissance style.
Well, that's what the tourist guides will tell you.
The building sits at the end of the platforms with a tower on each corner of the façade, indistinguishable from some provincial German town hall.
The stone is dirty.
The whole structure is slowly disintegrating.
But once inside the vaulted cash register, one can no longer doubt the size of the business whose westernmost gate of the station was.
The station was opened in August 1908 by a German consortium, the Anatoly-Baghdad Corporation.
Germany, which was late in the game of empires, intended to realize its ambitions to control the Middle East with this railway, which was supposed to lead to Damascus, Baghdad, and beyond what is now Saudi Arabia.
But German imperial ambitions collapsed during World War I.
Their dorms were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his irregular units.
The relative isolation from the surrounding territories, created by the frozen borders of the Cold War, is gone
British and colonial troops advanced from Egypt, pushing the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
And there was bad news for Hydarpaša station, too.
In 1917, an ammive train explosion destroyed its elaborate roof.
Turkish sources say it was sabotage.
Since then, it has been gradually crumbling and history has bypassed it.
But today, this gateway to Anatolia and further east serves - at least symbolically - to highlight the expanding horizons of Turkish diplomacy.
The ruling Justice and Development Party - the AKP - has created a whole new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation from the surrounding territories, created by the frozen borders of the Cold War, is gone.
A new policy is now in place - Turkey is engaged.
It is noteworthy that the Turkish Government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian factions Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq and Iran and, of course, with the European Union and the United States.
In order to examine the parameters of this new policy, I took a night train to the Turkish capital Ankara, where I was to meet one of the AKP's leading foreign policy experts, Turkish MEP Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning - about ten and a half hours later - after a sh, I arrived in the Turkish capital, designed as a new city for a secular state that wants to turn its back on its Otomanic past.
But the AKP, with its well-known Islamist roots, represents a paradigm shift in the Turkish consensus.
She aroused suspicion in the West, especially in Washington.
The taxi took me to the AKP headquarters, an ultra-modern stone and metal building deliberately built in an emerging suburb, surrounded by half-built department stores and power-trading shops, where middle managers in business suits - men and women - meet to do early morning business.
Suat Kiniklioglu could easily be a center-right politician from almost any other European political party.
Jacket, tie, I'm sure he had a Blackberry.
"The aim of the party's foreign policy is to reintegrate Turkey into its immediate vicinity.
The Cold War was an anomaly," he told me.
Turkey has been cut off from its border.
Today, they must look east and west at the same time.
It wasn't a choice.
He must have done both.
"But surely there will come a time," I asked, "when turkey may have to make a decision?"
"Turkey," he said, "did not want such a decision to take place."
Then he stressed what almost everyone I spoke to said almost by heart: Turkey's relations not only with the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus and around the Black Sea, are as good for Europe and the United States as they are for Turkey.
With Turkey on board, Europe as a whole seems to be able, metaphorically speaking, to go east on these tracks to Asia and the Middle East.
Back at Hydarpaša station, after another mostly sleepless night, I thought of the two German masters, Herr Ritter and Herr Cona, who watched this building be built a century ago.
How surprised they would be to find that Europe's ambitions in the Middle East can now, in large part, be in Turkish hands.
And as I waited at the port for the ferry back across the Bosphorus, I remembered that in those days Turkey was called the "sick man of Europe."
So it seems that at least then there was little doubt which continent should be entitled to this fascinating country.
