Bilingual debate: immersion in English
In this edition of Focused on Education, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi will discuss candidates' positions on bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, a California academic and director of education at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is the co-author of "Worse Than You Think: Why the Middle Class Needs To Choose Schools."
Effectively reaching Out to Hispanic voters is a tricky business.
Barack Obama's education agenda just proves it.
The Obama campaign notes that "African-American and Hispanic students are significantly less likely to graduate than white students," which is true.
To combat such performance gaps, Obama's education agenda advocates, among other things, "transitional bilingual education" for those who are just learning English.
But the question for Barack Obama is whether his commitment to bilingual education, which emphasizes the use of languages other than English in the classroom, is stronger than his interest in reducing performance gaps.
Take Sixth Street Prep, a charter elementary school in Los Angeles County East, for example.
The school's pupils are, in the vast majority of cases, Hispanic from low-income families.
More than a third of students, many of whom have only recently arrived, are still learning English.
Even so, in the 2008 state maths tests, an incredible 100% of fourth-graders reached the highest level.
Almost as amazing ninety-three percent of fourth-graders reached the highest level in state tests in English language and literature.
This incredible success was achieved by a different method than Obama prefers.
Sixth Street emphasizes control and practice, constant assessment of abilities and an excuseless approach.
Furthermore, and Obama should note this, according to Linda Mikels, director of Sixth Street, the school's pedagogical approach for those who are just learning English is "complete immersion."
Immersion in English emphasizes the almost privileged use of English in teaching.
Miss Mikels, who is against bilingual education, told me: "We had tremendous success with a brand new pupil from Mexico - after 12 months you would have walked into a classroom and not knowing which one it was."
"It works," she said, "it works for us."
Would Obama take school like Sixth Street Prep as a model of what other schools with large proportions of Hispanic and English learners should look like?
The school's results should make the answer to that question a matter of course, but his own party's education agenda (the National Education Association is a longtime advocate of bilingual education) and its own consistent support for bilingual education make it difficult to predict Obama's answer.
