Pride and obstacles to black life in a separate city
Hidden among the larger Orlando's streurous theme parks, a few miles from everything shiny, noisy and huge, lies a quiet city where the pride and demands of African-American life come to life.
Eatonville, the first all-black city to be incorporated into the state, where Zora Neale Hurston spent her childhood, is no longer as simple as she described it in 1935: "a city of five lakes, three croquet fields, three hundred brown skins, three hundred good swimmers, enough guava, two schools, and no prison."
Now it's a place of pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to eatonville's annual Zora! festival to pay tribute to Hurston, the most famous female writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
The city she described remains on the sidelines, even though it has made it a stop for tourists by including it in a Florida tourist guide created by the Depression-era Federal Writers project.
It's still as independent, dignified, and private as it was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted sharing their true feelings with a white man who "knows so little about us that he doesn't even know what he's missing."
Even today, in a year when a black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, is calling for an open debate about race, many locals remain wary of the views of strangers.
"We pay great attention to how our story is told," says Hortense Jones, 59, who has lived here since birth and is a member of the oldest parish in the city.
"It's got to be right."
Eatonville has long been characterized as a paradox of triumph and effort.
It is both a historical model of black rise and a community of nearly 2,400 people, where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is a center of literature, but also oaks shielded by an example of Southern rural black culture - sometimes despised, sometimes praised - that arose from American slavery.
It's not surprising that the locals are both proud and protective.
And the worries about eatonville's idea really started with Zora, which is the only way hurstons are called here.
She introduced her hometown to the world through heartfelt books full of dialect such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
