With a great drumbeat in her life and literature, Hurston led readers to the store of Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clark, and then turned to more personal places.
"To the left of the road," she wrote, "is a white brown-decorated modern national school with well-maintained courtyards and playgrounds that Howard Miller always takes care of, even if he can't read or write much."
She also mentioned widow Dash's new husband and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of all kinds and anything that fits into an hour-long hotel."
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston connected Eatonville with self-government, but also with illiteracy, remarried marriage, and sex.
This was clearly not typical Fodor's publishing house.
In fact, it wasn't a portrait that everyone appreciated.
"Zora said it the way it was," says Ella Dinkins, 90, one of johnson's girls, who made Hurston immortal by quoting men who sang dirty songs about their beauty.
"Some people didn't like it," she added.
Hurston is still remembered here as a chipper eccentric who often returned after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Augustus Franklin, 77, remembers that most of the time, when she arrived in the city, she arrived unannounced in a huge Chevrolet, smoking and wearing pants in a city that is still proud of its dignified dress.
Most residents were fascinated, Franklin said, but many sneered.
"The people have always been happy to see Zora," Franklin said.
But, he added, swinging on a chair on the back terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, "she never stayed too long."
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were taken out of print.
Eatonville, along with the rest of the world, seemed to have forgotten her.
Although she was once a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she had previously lived.
There were no major funeral ceremonies or large public readings in Eatonville.
