The proposal came at a time when Eatonville was still coming out of a difficult historical period.
Forced integration, along with other things, ended the relatively idyllic isolation of this community.
In the 1950s, the struggle to mix races brought hatred to the threshold of the community.
"At the time, a bunch of white guys, they came in and threw oranges and stuff at people sitting on the side," Franklin said.
"Actually, we had a lady who was killed.
They threw a watermelon out of the car."
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston questioned the Supreme Court's demand for forced integration, saying his decision in the Brown case against the Education Chamber was "insulting rather than glorifying to my race."
Residents now claim that the desegregation of schools, while positive in some areas, has reduced cohesion in Eatonville and undermined the courage of the local youth.
