Memorable lives: Vernon Handley and William Woodruff
Mark Brown writes: As Guildford's music director since 1962, Vernon "Tod" Handley (obituary, September 11) was in charge of the Guildford Philharmonic Orchestra and Choir.
As part of the district's music plan, he founded an excellent proteus youth choir a year later.
He was supposed to be under 21, but by the time Proteus last sang in 1979, there were almost 30 of us - we just refused to give up the chorus.
The name "Proteus" (mythological shape changer) represented the willingness and ability of the choir to embark on any music presented to it - whether madrigals or Messiaen, either alone or with the whole orchestra.
The musical adaptability created by such a young choir was often overwhelming, always exciting, all thanks to the inspiration of that one man and the enthusiasm for music that remained absolutely unchanged all the time.
How often did Tod just tell us to "let the music speak for itself."
He said, "The composer knows what he wants.
It's all in the music.
Then sing it! "
His baton technique was very clear and precise, but it was neither dictatorial nor flowery.
Wherever the standard of music was, it always lifted it up.
John Frayn Turner writes:
If any conductor was to be knighted, it was Vernon Handley.
I knew him well in the two decades he conducted Guildford Philharomines from 1962 to 1982.
I have reviewed over 100 of his concerts over the last 40 years or so and I can honestly say that I have never been disappointed in any of them - and I have been inspired many times.
Tod Handley had such a great combination of size and personal modesty.
He hated conductors who, in his words, simply "dragged one or two soaked stones around the world."
He's going to be missed by a lot of us.
William Woodruff
Professor John Beckett writes:
Your obituary of William Woodruff (September 25) states that "in 1946 he returned to economic history at Oxford and in 1950 became a researcher at Houblon-Norman... and at the same time studied at BSc, MA and PhD".
This is based on Woodruff's author's note in Beyond Nab End, but it's not accurate.
From 1946 to 1953 he taught economics history at the University of Nottingham, and at that time he finished his dissertation on the British rubber industry, led by Professor J.D. Chambers, and subsequently published it in 1958 as a publication of the British Rubber Industry.
Indeed, he spent the years 1950-51 in America as a researcher at Houblon-Norman and the summer of 1952 at Illinois, Harvard and New York University.
In 1953, he finally left Nottingham and moved to Illinois.
It is not known why Woodruff moved on to this part of his career.
Muslim graves desecrated after Austrian right-wing break
Heinz-Christian Strache, left, of the Austrian right-wing Freedom Party, and Filip Dewinter of the Belgian right-wing Vlaams Belang party attend a rally in Antwerp on Thursday, January 17, 2008.
They carry signs similar to road signs that show mosques crossed out by a red line.
Police accuse right-wing extremists of desecrating a Muslim cemetery in Austria on the same weekend that extreme right-wing parties made huge gains in the general election.
More than 90 graves in the cemetery in the town of Traun near Linz were severely damaged sometime between Friday evening and this morning, and police believe it was an organized event.
The culprits spray-painted Jewish symbols on some graves, such as David's Star, but detectives believe it may have been an attempt to disguise the motives of extremists led by hatred of Muslim immigrants.
It is unclear whether the incident was connected to the election in any way.
A spokesman for the Islamic community said they were "deeply shocked" by the news of the desecration, which comes as the Muslim fasting month of Ramadan approaches its end.
Austria, meanwhile, is entering the soul-searching round after swinging to the right in yesterday's parliamentary elections.
The two far-right parties, which together won more than 30 percent of the vote, the Freedom Party and the Union for the Future of Austria, waged a vehemently anti-immigrant campaign, and some of their slogans were condemned by critics as xenophobic.
Heinz-Christian Strache, leader of the Freedom Party, which won more than 18 percent of the vote, protested against headscarves and burqas in the campaign and even expressed his opposition to foods that are perceived to be related to Islam.
At his last meeting with voters in Vienna, he spoke of a "European brotherhood" to prevent the rise of Islam.
Both sides are trying to ban the construction of mosques and minarets, arguing that they are political symbols of the ongoing Islamization of Austria and Europe.
Surveys and analyses carried out immediately after the elections, which put the extreme right as the strongest political bloc in the country, suggest that this change was mainly due to young voters who are worried about their future in the European Union.
Gary Glitter is not allowed on a trip abroad
Gary Glitter, a glamrock star who was convicted of child sexual abuse, was banned from travel to France and Spain by the court.
Officials imposed the six-month ban on Glitter after he informed monitoring authorities that he planned to travel to Spain via France.
Kent Police agreed to the travel ban last Thursday after handing over evidence of Glitter's past child sexual abuse cases to officials.
Glitter, real name Paul Gadd, did not attend the hearing at Ashford Crown Court in Kent, but was represented by corker binning lawyers.
A spokesman for the court service said: "On Thursday 25 September at Ashford Crown Court, Kent Police applied for an order to prevent Mr Paul Gadd from crossing the border into France and Spain until 25 March.
Paul Gadd did not attend in person."
Glitter, 64, informed authorities that he wished to travel abroad, as required by his sex offenders' record.
He must notify the authorities if he wants to travel abroad for more than three days.
They must also hand over the planned departure date to the police a week in advance.
If he neglected the duty to inform the authorities, he could be sentenced to five years.
Kent Police said it would not discuss individual cases of Glitter's possible travels around the county.
A Kent Police spokeswoman said: "Kent Police will do everything necessary to protect children in this country or abroad.
From our point of view, it is easier to track someone who stays in Britain, because we have extensive systems that handle potential dangers more effectively.
Protecting kent residents is a top priority for Kent Police and we are working hard to monitor the behaviour of recorded sex offenders to minimise any danger to the public."
Glitter returned to Britain last month after spending 27 months in a Vietnamese prison for abusing two girls, aged 10 and 11.
When he was released, he flew to Bangkok to board a flight to London.
But he said he wasn't feeling well, and refused to fly to London.
Thai authorities wouldn't let him pass passport control and he eventually flew to Hong Kong.
Chinese authorities also refused to allow him to enter, and he flew back to Bangkok, where Thai police and immigration officials insisted on his return to Britain.
On August 22, he finally arrived at Heathrow Terminal 3 and stayed there while his solicitor David Corker went to Uxbridge's Lowest Criminal Court in west London, while Scotland Yard successfully requested an order ordering him to register as a sex offender.
Glitter was previously jailed for four months in the UK for possessing child pornography.
An Interior Ministry source said Jacqui Smith, the Home Secretary, was calm and glad Glitter had been prevented from going to France and Spain.
"To capture the true character, I take pictures of the master off-stage." Günther Bauer - photographer
No heels, no ruffles, no costumes.
Only the essence of great flamenco masters, detached from focusing on interpretation - I will only get the relaxed expression of a man or a woman.
Artist on one side.
On the other hand, human.
Inseparable, privacy aside, at those moments far from the audience - that's when you can see the intimate gesture, the depth of the glance caught, or the passionate gesticulation of hands that are carefree because they're not about to step onto the stage.
German Günther Bauer alternates the theatricality of performances with singers, dancers and guitarists with the lesser-known face of masters in "Flamenco-people".
With this in mind, the photographer compiles a unique iconography of flamenco from different backgrounds.
The exhibition, which takes place as part of the Mes de la Fotografía Flamenca Photography Month program, "reflects the ever-growing international importance of flamenco," says the author, explaining that "Flamenco-people" "can be any kind of people, but if you look at the photos, you will find that these are not typical images of artists on the stage.
These people portrayed "on the street" are artists able to bring passion, sadness, joy to the scene... and completely captivate the audience.
To capture the personality of these artists, it is not necessary to take pictures on stage.
He carries his personality and character inside.
I was interested in creating a relaxed atmosphere that would allow me to capture the personality of flamenco greats.
Enchanted by the "Cante de las Minas" festival, Bauer began the long journey of portraiting flamenco singers, guitarists and dancers on a board camera in 1997.
They are portraits that, thanks to the choice of camera and material, resemble classic photography.
The use of different stylistic means is contrary to the classical basis of the film and lends it a contemporary spirit, an idea that Bauer himself says is mirrored by flamenco: "Music with very traditional roots, but it continues to surprise and evolve."
What attracts the audience is not the action of the dance, singing or play itself, but the personality and character of the artist.
The search for the moment when we encounter the most important, the spirit that appears in the way of perception, existence and experience, was and is the constant of the work presented during these days in the Gallery of El Fotómata.
This selection of nearly seventy photographed artists is shaped by well-known flamenco figures such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales and Vicente Amigo, among others.
The project has become a kind of flamenco anthology and will soon see a book edition containing portraits on display.
Two years ago, Bauer's passion for portraiture led him to the idea of repeating the idea on "Portraits of Sports Veterans" ("SportARTproject").
Although their concept is different from "Flamenco-people", the photographer admits that "taking pictures of people, getting to know them and being able to enter their lives for a moment, whether longer or short - that's my passion.
I think in photography, portraiture is the most difficult genre.
A person meets or encounters people, personalities he sometimes doesn't even know, or they only give him a few minutes to take pictures.
Despite similar circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to realize my ideas."
The collection of portraits of contemporary flamenco called "Flamenco-people" is on display at the El Fotómata Gallery at 20 De la Mata, parallel to the Alameda de Hércules, and can be visited until 16 October.
