Carmen Tórtola Valencia, from her father, Florenç Tórtola Ferrer, and her mother, Andalusanka (Georgina Valencia Valenzuela), was born in triana, and moved to London with her family when she was three.
She danced modern dance and focused on oriental dances.
She lived a life of passion, pioneering female emancipation like Isadora Duncan, Virginia Woolf, and Sarah Bernhardt.
She was a Buddhist and a vegetarian and fought to remove the corset, which prevented women from moving freely.
The life of this woman influenced by the dance and aesthetic revolution of interwar Europe enchanted Isabele Bayón.
"I wanted to work with Pepa Gamboa and she designed this character for me - I thought it was incredible."
According to the dancer, "it's not about telling her life, it's about grasping the soul.
The names of her dance performances reminded me of the rhythms of flamenco.
So the "butterfly dance" reminded me of guajira or "snake dance" some kind of thong.
Her dance was sensual and they told me that my dance also corresponded to this aesthetic," she says.
The performance includes two exceptional personalities: Miguel Pod, who will sing Isabelle in one performance as well as in "Open Door" (La puerta abierta), and dance teacher Matilde Coral, who made an exception and agreed to collaborate with her former student.
