"Car bee" prevents collisions
Nissan was inspired to make progress in developing accident-fighting technologies in nature this time, specifically in bees.
This Japanese company has created a robot that takes as a model the flying of bees, thus preventing collisions.
This is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, which represents the first step in precipitation prevention technologies.
Engineers at the Nissan Motor Co. Center for Technical Progress. the robot was developed in collaboration with the Center for Advancement in Scientific and Technological Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo in Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Public Relations' Director General for Technology, Research and Brand Development, the BR23C is presented as an extension of Nissan's four safety shield zones.
The robot is designed to strengthen the ability to prevent collisions in cars of this brand.
During the flight, each bee creates its own personal space of an oval shape, which is very similar to the safety shield of a Nissan.
However, the most important are folded bee eyes, which are able to see in all directions at an angle of more than 300 degrees, allowing the bee to fly in its personal space without stopping.
Engineers designed what they called a Laser Range Finder when creating this visual feature.
It records obstacles up to two metres within a radius of 180 degrees in front of the BR23C, calculates the distance of the object and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately converts it into a collision warning.
"At the moment when an obstacle is recorded, the robot imitates the bee's movements and immediately changes direction by turning the wheels to a right or even greater angle to prevent collision.
The biggest difference from any existing system is that all evasive maneuvers are completely instinctive.
If this were not the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, Director of the Mobile Laboratory and Chief Engineer of the project.
Unlike bees, the robot cannot move up and down even diagonally, its movement is limited to only two dimensions and to the direction in which it is made possible by rotating its wheels, but not in an infinite number of directions and possibilities, as in the case of bees.
In addition to acceleration and deceleration, Nissan also used the rotation function to prevent the robots from colliding.
"The device only needs to process the information every few seconds and act on this data.
It does not require information retention or logical intuition from previous maneuvers, allowing it to function without interruption with only two dozen KB of memory.
This may come as a surprise to you, but we're not talking about a gig or a mega in memory."
This is the first step in the development of new instant collision prevention technologies, a technology that Nissan predicts will be used in serial cars in a decade.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and last longer than lithium-ion batteries.
Another possible future use of this technology could be to incorporate the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system, which would lead the driver to his destination while avoiding obstacles on the way.
