Talking in your sleep
Some kids talk at night.
I don't mean the ones who wake up and tell us something that happened the day before, but children who talk while they sleep.
When it happens the first time, it may get you started, but it's actually meaningless.
It is a harmless sleep disorder called somnilokvie.
It's quite frequent, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure many of you were told he was talking in his sleep last night.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadically (for example, once in a lifetime with high fevers), or with greater regularity (every day, once a week, once every few months...), the next day the child does not remember anything.
There's not just one reason to explain her arrival.
It is often associated with other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night rages, enuresis nocturna (night wetting) or sleepwalking, but this may not be the case.
As mentioned earlier, it can often be accompanied by very high fevers, stressful or inflamed situations.
In any case, this is a little-researched phenomenon.
The intensity with which it appears is also varied.
The child can speak in a calm voice, say individual words, whisper, or vice versa (screams, cries, long speeches...).
In cases where it manifests itself with great force, it would be advisable to observe the child and consult a specialist to see if he has any problem that causes him great anxiety and in this way manifests himself.
We said that this is a harmless disorder, therefore it is not treated only if it is associated with another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, if it is associated with apnea syndrome or permanent stress).
However, what we can do is keep in mind a few very simple preventive measures, such as:
Trying not to upset the baby too much before he goes to sleep.
So look for quiet games and avoid scary or somewhat violent TV programs or series.
In very nervous children and those who are given the opportunity to relax, it is possible to use relaxation techniques that will help them gain some inner peace.
This will allow the child to sleep more peacefully.
When somnilokvie appears, try to remain calm.
Remind yourself that it is harmless to the child and that from what happened, the next day she will not remember anything.
Useful advice
Don't wake him up.
It's useless because he's not conscious and you're going to interrupt his sleep.
Even when he speaks, he sleeps, and thus rests.
Remember that if you think that they are very distressed several times in a row, it would be advisable to turn to advice or find out what causes such anxiety in a child.
If you understand what he's saying (which isn't so common), avoid the temptation to interrogate him and pull information out of him.
It won't do any good, because when he's asleep, he's not conscious to organize his thoughts.
Plus, you'll hear what he's saying, but you don't know what he's dreaming about, so be very careful how you interpret the information and what conclusions you're drawn.
Never tell a child you can ask him about his secret at night.
Not even for fun.
That's causing a lot of anxiety.
Just don't worry, it's nothing bad, it's just an episode that only lasts a few minutes.
