A week after unveiling their tentative deal, the two banks explained that MUFG intends to buy 9.9% of Morgan Stanley's ordinary shares at a single price of $25.25, representing a total of $3 billion.
The agreed price is 19% lower than the book value of the securities as at 31 August.
MUFG is investing an additional $6 billion to acquire convertible securities that will give it a 10% return and have an exchange price of $31.25.
Morgan Stanley clarified that the entire operation will take place on the basis of an average uniform price of $29, or 28% below its current rate.
Still, Morgan Stanley shares were losing 6.79% to reach $23.07 around 5 p.m. Greenwich Mean Time.
"This strategic merger represents an important opportunity on the way to accelerating Morgan Stanley's transition to bank holding status," said John Mack, ceo of the U.S. group.
The new status was adopted by Morgan Stanley last week, which is intended to allow it to variously differentiate its activities, but it also places it under the supervision of the Federal Reserve Bank.
Its merger with MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis is forcing Wall Street's biggest aces to take a much more cautious approach than before.
Among other things, the terms presented on Monday show that the deal has been altered over the past few days: last Monday, Morgan only announced that it would sell up to 20% of its shares to the Japanese for about $8.5 billion.
