Interview - Blood that's sure again
Héma-Québec celebrated its 10th anniversary yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, was rightly happy, as Heema-Quebec became one of the most reliable and efficient blood suppliers in the world.
Above all, he regained the trust of the public, who were severely shaken after the contaminated blood scandal of the 1980s and 1990s.
As is widely known, the State Blood Reserve administered by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Department was contaminated with the Immune Deficiency Virus (HIV) and the Hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this drama and a wave of public resentment, in February 1994 the Canadian government launched a public inquiry, chaired by Judge Horace Krever, to explain the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to formulate recommendations that such a disaster should not happen again.
While Judge Krever was delaying the report, some provinces set in place a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, Gélinea's committee played this role.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were set up in Canada: Hema-Quebec, which was to be managed by Quebec, and the Canadian Blood Society, to supply all provinces and territories.
"When Héma-Québec started its activities in 1998, barely 38% of people still had confidence in quebec's blood system," dr. Décary recalls.
"The situation was daunting.
By constantly trying to increase the safety of blood products and by working constantly in this area over the following years, we have regained public trust," he says, proudly adding that in early 2008, nearly 94% of Quebec's population trusted Héma-Quebec.
Dr. Décary, however, does not lose sight of the fact that "trust is something very fragile."
Since its establishment on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
"At that time, we saw many cases in Europe of human form of mad cow disease, a new variant of the disease called Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease," says the woman who has led the company since its founding in 1998.
"And we had no idea whether this disease could spread through blood.
We therefore relied on one of the basic recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports, according to which, when we do not know and when the spread of a serious disease is at stake, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by brain degeneration inevitably leading to death, exclusionary measures must be taken.
Therefore, in April 1999, we refused blood from people who had been in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
A few years ago, it was safely proven that this disease is transmitted through blood.
So this episode showed us that sticking to the precautionary principle made sense."
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for detecting HIV appeared on the market: tests using nucleic acid (NAT), which allow the presence of the virus itself to be detected directly in the donor blood, and not the presence of antibodies on which the tests used before were based.
NAT tests have made it possible to shorten the deaf period that occurs between the moment of infection of the patient and the moment when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
We were able to shorten this period to less than a week.
This has significantly reduced the risk that some donors might be infected without their knowledge and without us figuring it out.
These improvements have made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of getting AIDS through blood transfusion.
One in 12 million people are now at risk of getting HIV-contaminated blood.
"In other words, it means that 12 million blood products will need to be distributed before someone gets HIV.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take 24 years for the first case of HIV transmission through a blood product to occur.
I believe that today we can get or prescribe the blood transfusion necessary for recovery in complete peace," says the head of the Héma-Québek leadership.
"The challenge for the next decade is to keep our products safety.
We never know what disease-prolific element can appear in the system.
Just last year, the chikungunya virus appeared on Reunion Island, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted to the blood by stinging insects.
We need to be vigilant at all times," dr. Décary stresses that, in addition to safe supply, Héma-Québec must also count on sufficient supply.
"Needs are growing as the population ages.
As a result of more aggressive cancer treatment, patients often need a new dose of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing population also has implications for the blood donor network, which on average consists of only 3% of Quebecers eligible for donation."
Any healthy person at least 18 years old, according to the criteria of admissibility, but can donate blood only once every 56 days, that is, six times a year.
On average, 14% of people offering blood are not admitted because they are carriers of AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have visited a country where mud fever is raging, they are excluded for a year.
"With this 3%, we can maintain a condition that meets the needs of hospitals.
Shortcomings are very rare.
However, members of the donor network need to be supplemented in proportion to how they age and can no longer donate blood.
However, persuading people to give blood is difficult, especially to keep them and encourage them to become regular donors.
Life today is so unfettered that we rarely find an hour to donate blood," says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissue, such as bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs, and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analysed, processed and frozen before being stored at Heema-Quebec, which also manages Quebec's only public umbilical cord blood bank.
The umbilical cord, previously considered biomedical waste, abounds in blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases such as leukemia.
"A few weeks ago, we celebrated the deposit of our 1,000th umbilical cord blood sample into the bank, and we expect to take over 1,000 a year.
We should start offering them for transplants early next year," says Dr. Décary, who describes the cord blood collection program as very popular.
"Some mothers are disappointed that they do not have access to it," because Héma-Québec does not have the resources to offer this comprehensive and expensive program to all hospitals in Quebec.
