Opinions - Barrick Gold's Orwellian Discourse
In a September 17 issue, Le Devoir published a letter from Patrick J. Garver, executive vice president of Barrick Gold, a Canadian mining company.
With Orwellian logic, it confirms that the world's largest gold producer has launched a libel suit against three authors and a poor small publishing house in order to provoke a "transparent public debate" and is asking them for six million.
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, they judge not truthfulness, especially in the case of libel prosecutions, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, Garver completely de-ersted this crucial distinction.
Or is barrick gold the best way to have a public debate, to bankrupt anyone who dares to defend the opposite position?
Whatever the outcome of the trial, the authors and publisher of Noir Canada will be forced to spend respectable sums to be prepared to defend themselves and fight a very unbalanced battle with an army of lawyers supported by the near-free pockets of a mining company.
Moreover, the tactic in these unbalanced fights often consists in ruining defendants in order to enforce conciliation proceedings that shut up the opposing party's mouth and, moreover, scare anyone who dares to pursue the matter.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it should have introduced its view of the matter to public opinion.
Contrary to what is happening in several countries where Barrick Gold operates, in Canada, the debate normally consists of exchanging ideas, not blows with a tb;
So it was not enough for mining companies to open their books, their documentation, and to establish a real debate through newspapers, media, publications, and funding of independent scientific teams that could shed light on the matter.
Barrick Gold, however, does not seem to have confidence in public opinion, and he has shemahly rejected petitions and letters in support of the authors of Noir Canada.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he can demand "public debate" while contemptuate the views of the same public?
In the vice president's world, this word seems to refer only to boldly paid attorneys, and not to all Canadians; this is a rather narrow conception of this concept.
In a democracy, even slanderers have the right to speak out.
Barrick Gold does not understand - or does not want to understand - that the public that supports the authors and publishers of Noir Canada is doing so primarily because it rejects the brutal ways of the mining company.
The public is prepared to hear Barrick and assess the case, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, not in what many perceive as a prosecution in which the defendant's mouth is to be blocked (as part of its pursuit of the "public debate", Barrick has, incidentally, just issued an official invitation to the authors of Noir Canada to officially inform them to stop using the term...).
Aside from Garver's surreal speech, the prosecution initiated by Barrick Gold is a direct attack on the university's freedom to research and seek truth that is essential to any democratic society.
Overall, it denies the right to cite credible sources and to debate the facts and interpretations that constitute the very basis of intellectual activity.
If, in a country like Canada, it is impossible to study and discuss topics that the rich companies of this world do not like without being subjected to repeated prosecution, who else will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could have created it if it had followed the scientific standards used by noir canada's authors.
He's entitled to an answer.
The university environment to which we belong has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's overreaching lawsuit makes it clear that, contrary to what it claims, it has no desire to have a transparent debate.
This is a loss for the university world, as it is for public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place measures to limit this type of wrongful prosecution.
The Operation to Save Wall Street - Democrats and Republicans Understand
Yesterday, the Bush administration and congressional leaders, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement on the largest rescue economic plan since the great crisis of the 1930s.
A new version of the plan to use $700 billion to slow the financial crisis that has been stricching Wall Street for months has yet to be approved by both houses of Congress.
In particular, it foresees: better control of the applications of elected representatives, new mechanisms ensuring the repayment of public money deposited, new measures to capture the number of houses seized due to non-payment, as well as the right to monitor the level of wages paid to executives of rescued firms.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, House Minority Leader Nancy Pelosi and Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news just after midnight yesterday, after completing a two-day negotiating marathon.
"We have made great striving and reached an agreement that is effective in the markets," said Bush administration official Henry Paulson.
"Everything has been done to keep the real economy and ordinary Americans safe from the crisis currently underway on Wall Street," the Democrat explained.
"This is a crucial point: if we don't, the trauma, chaos, and disruption to Americans' daily lives will be enormous," said Republican Judd Gregg.
Over the past few hours, negotiations have started to take a turn for fear of the effect that another failure would have on investors' mood.
The set time limit was the opening of the markets this morning.
Both CANDIDATES for US President were invited to the negotiations later, and both expressed their more in support of the agreement, but did not neglect to express their dissatisfaction that such a last resort had to be resorted to such a last resort.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama credited the agreement with some measures, not least one aimed at allowing homeowners to keep their homes, and measures on the wages of labor leaders of state-rescued firms.
"When we ask taxpayers to take special measures because of the irresponsibility of some people, there is nothing to congratulate.
However, these measures are necessary," he explained on the television.
His Republican rival, John McCain, who was asked by another network whether he would vote for the proposed plan, replied, "I'd like to see the details, but I hope so."
"The rough features I have read [show] that this is something that we will all have to digest and that will be able to move forward.
It is simply unacceptable to choose inaction," he said.
The $700 billion plan aims to buy back dubious claims and risky and unsellable assets of U.S. financial institutions with taxpayers' money.
The plan comes after 14 months of crisis unleashed by the bursting of the housing bubble, which first led to the collapse of subprimes, then shifted to other, more widespread forms of credit (PCAA) and resulted in a cash freeze and the disintegration of banks and financial institutions.
The collapse of the first draft agreement last week was caused by Republican members.
Ever since Democrats agreed that some of the "toxic" assets of struggling companies would only be liable by the government but not bought, there has been a belief that the impasse is over.
In an effort to bring the opposing views together in Congress, a measure was added stipulating that the government could introduce new fees to help it recover its deposit if it had to take losses for five years as a result of the program.
The new plan foresees a first deposit of $250 billion, to which an additional $100 billion can be added if the president deems it necessary.
The additional $350 billion should be approved by Congress in a new vote.
In exchange for its help, Washington will acquire shares in the rescued companies, which, if profitable, will pay him dividends and which it can resell when it is over.
The federal government will be able to delay foreclosure procedures related to the loans covered by the plan, as well as set limits on the amount of valuation and compensation paid to executives of affected firms.
The architects of the plan would like to put it to a vote in the House of Representatives today and in the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all the efforts made, it is not yet certain that their plan will have the green light.
Yesterday, votes continued to rise against the project in both the Republican and Democratic camps.
"It's pretty obvious that Washington can't hear you," Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Committee, said to voters.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But making money on taxpayers is not the solution."
Democratic Representative Brad Sherman, moderator of a group of congressmen dubbed the "committee of skeptics," presents the matter differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred esteemed economics professors, including three Nobel laureates, have written to us: we ask Congress not to rush too much and carefully examine which path to take," he said yesterday.
At the same time, it was reaffirmed in Europe that this crisis is a global crisis.
Following the extraordinary meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalisation of the Fortis Banking Group for €11.2 billion (US$16.3 billion).
Intervention by the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary after French bank BNP Paribas announced that it was withdrawing from the purchase of its competitor, which has been on the verge of collapse since losing €2 billion ($2.9 billion) as a result of the risky real estate loan crisis in the United States.
Fortis employs 85,000 people, is one of Europe's 20 largest banks and one of the top ten insurers.
"We will not lose this money," Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
"In return, we gain the right to vote in the bank and influence.
This is what savers and households can appreciate in these uncertain times."
On the other side of the English Channel, meanwhile, the British government appears to have launched the nationalisation of another bank affected by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government was to take over all existing bradford and bringley bank loans, more than $41 billion ($75.5 billion) of which were loans to buy real estate.
According to its announcement yesterday, the Spanish bank Santander will buy the branches and accounts of british bank clients.
Bradford and Bringley will be the second bank after Northern Rock that the British government must nationalize since the financial crisis began.
Paul Newman (1925-2008) - Death of a socially engaged icon
His azure-eyed beauty has long been his trump card, according to others, weakness.
Did this American actor, with a charming smile, break out of narcissism?
Yes and no.
The shyness, sensitivity, and unceasing talent that were his own also distanced him from the power category that breeds real stars.
But what a long-distance runner he was!
Paul Newman died Friday at the age of 83 at his ranch in Connecticut from lung cancer and remains one of the last icons of the fat years of American cinema.
Less spectacular than Brando, to whom he was similar and had long been a kind of rival on the screen, Newman was a more cautious actor, certainly a more fragile, but also an apostle of freedom and the disintegration of dramatic conventions.
Mixed blood often produces beautiful children.
Born in Ohio in 1925, his father was a German Jew and his mother was Hungarian.
From these European roots, one of the famous faces of the American dream was born.
Without exaggerated ego, which is the last sign of quality.
Because it saw this whole country in love with a self-made man, a warrior in the Pacific War wounded in battle who studied acting at Yale in the early 1950s, then attended New York's Actor's Studio and celebrated triumph in theater, television, and early film.
The same man who fought for civil rights was also a racing driver, ranked second in the 24-hour race at Le Mans in 1979, and a sex symbol, despite having been a model couple with actress Joanne Woodward since 1958.
With him also leave the shady places of this hidden, discreet, socially engaged star, allergic to the fuss of his own show business, which will forever remain mysterious to some extent.
A decent man, in the noblest sense of the word.
Paul Newman's departure this weekend has made film lovers dizzy, while his big roles compete on the black screen of memories.
After that, he defils more than half a century of ever-changing American seventh art.
Resuappeaming in memory is the charming cowboy from Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid (1969), a young man who rejects his sensual wife (Elizabeth Taylor) in Cat on a Hot Roof, a 1958 adaptation of Tennessee Williams.
From a less distant past (1990), we recall his sensitive Mr. Bridge, disturbed at an advanced age by a marriage that did not live up to all expectations.
So many other Paul Newmans have made history.
Boxer Rocky Graziano, the battered, violent, unforgettable delinquent from Robert Wise's Somebody Up There Likes Me, a role intended for James Dean, taken over after his death in 1956, made Newman truly famous.
A likeable gangster in the absolutely great The Sting (Backstabbing), oscar for best picture in 1973.
A bitter and vindictive billiards player in Robert Rossen's the amazing The Hustler (1961), he will play the same character in Martin Scorsese's The Color of Money, which will give him only one Oscar out of seven nominations in 1987.
This face traveling through the ages, that was him.
And he again.
Different eras compete with each other in his career.
Young people know him mainly because of the iconic Slap Shot by George Roy Hill (1977) from the role of Reggie Dunlop, an unconventional hockey coach.
Fans reunited with him in 1994 at The Hudsucker Proxy of the Coen brothers.
He ended his career as the godfather of the Irish mafia in Sam Mendes' Road to Perdition in 2003.
Unlike several film legends who left the business relatively soon, Newman remained in the business for a long time, though he denounced Hollywood with its gildedness, pomp, and concessions.
The French filmmaker Bertrand Tavernier, not without humor, considered it "a living challenge of underplaying," judging that he pushed too hard in his performances.
For the beautiful Paul Newman, to whom the roles came as a tray, the profession was not always so tender.
But he played the first lovers less often than outsiders: neurotics, alcoholics, crooks, and desperate men, whose downs and rebellions were reflected in his perfect features.
As director, Newman revealed little-known aspects of his shy sensibilities.
His 1968 film Rachel, Rachel (based on a novel by Canadian Margaret Laurence), starring his wife Joanne Woodward, gives a sensitive female portrait full of melancholy.
In 1984, he dedicated the 1984 film Harry and Son, a work of shame and sadness, to his son Scott, whom he lost due to an overdose.
In a flurry of tributes to Newman yesterday, his great friend and former band mate Robert Redford (who starred together in The Sting and Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid) said sadly, "His presence has made my life and this country better."
Generosity, love of life, such are the main qualities of a deceased actor.
Aside from his legendary career, the great civil rights activist, ecology, independent film, opponent of Hollywood's decline, is also leaving.
We used to see his likeness on bottles of wine vinegar, sauces, biscuits and other foods, which may have seemed rather tawy to us, although at first it was a gag.
However, the proceeds from the sale went to the account of his Foundation for a Difficult Childhood.
Newman was engaged in society until the last moment, rather than lulled into glory.
He left a letter to his five daughters containing the following sentences: "Always and to the end, your father was grateful to his happy planet.
It was an honor to be here."
And it was an honor for us to be able to follow the life path of such a prescient and magnanimous American artist.
And besides, after all, a model citizen.
What was produced in the invoice factory Zuschlag & spol.?
Shortly, on October 8, the trial will begin in the criminal proceedings against János Zuschlag and his associates.
Among other crimes, including forgery of documents, the politician and his associates are accused of fraud committed by a long-term and systematic criminal organisation, resulting in extremely significant damage.
According to the prosecutor's office, they used the money obtained in the tenders for their own purposes and often admissed the completion of tasks with fictitious invoices.
Money from the state and local governments - totalling about 65 million forints - went partly to fiatal baloldal's coffers, partly to the pockets of individuals.
The method, which was also reported by the investigating authority, was that the money raised in the tenders was collected on the basis of invoices for which there was no real consideration and the commitments entered into by the associations were never met.
According to the indictment, a large portion of the invoices were false.
The forms for these invoices came from the Józsefváros market, the round stamps were made in Kiskunhalasi.
The names of which companies are to be used for the production of invoices were decided, among other things, on a tour of the northern shore of Balaton, to which János Zuschlag sent Isttan Lados.
According to his statement, the former should have been looking for guesthouses and restaurants.
In them, he applied for bills for his consumption, according to which invoices submitted in the framework of tenders issued, among other things, by the Ministry of Youth and Sport, the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs and the Municipality of the Capital were produced.
The invoices were mostly issued by István Lados and his partner András Őri, who, according to our information, most often wrote the reports needed to obtain subsidies.
On his "study trip", Lados looked for a pub.
According to two invoices issued by Zuschlage and his associates in 2003, this hospitality establishment provided catering for a group of 90 from biztos pont.
However, according to the head of the company, so many people would not fit in this facility at once.
Similarly, the invoice issued in the summer of 2002 to a foundation called Jobb Jövőért, later Együtt and Harmadik Évezredért, was teeming with formal and content errors.
The guesthouse in Badacsonytomaji had only three rooms, more than ten people could not sleep in it one evening, yet one hundred and thirty guests were listed on the invoice.
However, the fillers of the forms with a rich imagination overdue this even when they put on the documents a company also engaged in hospitality - Pigal s.r.o., whose accounts, according to the information provided to the public prosecutor's office, did not even contain documents in the name of Jobb Jövőért and Hoppá.
Győző Farkas, head of hvg.hu, said that when he was summoned to the prosecutor's office and shown invoices, he immediately knew they were fake documents.
"The name of our business and our tax number were in the wrong place on the stamp."
As he added, in addition to the formalities, the fact that they accommodated 100 people according to the invoice, they have only eleven rooms that do not have such a large capacity.
In addition, the invoice also stated catering, and their restaurant has not worked for a long time.
Zealous invoice manufacturers were also unconvinced that the budapest travel agency was only organising foreign trips, and foolishly cited the invoice with a cash payment, which was also not the same as the company's billing practice, as a service for arranging a trip to Hungary.
Moreover, as was shown in the course of the investigation, they also stated VAT in the document, although the organisation of trips to countries outside the European Union was exempt from VAT.
The four documents issued to the Jobb Jövőért Foundation by Hotel Révfülöp s.r.o. did not agree, inter alia, on the amount of VAT. The company's activities are not covered by the 25% but by 15% VAT, in addition, hotel employees issued only printed invoices, but the invoice produced was handwritten.
In addition, the "publishers" spoiled the invoice by, for example, laying out, as it became clear from an investigation by the public prosecutor's office, as a road transport activity that the company based on investment advice had not originally carried out.
Moreover, the fact that the invoices issued to the Együtt and Harmadik Évezredért foundations and to XXI.
As in the case of Ravenna k.s. or the Sports Camp in Kunfehértó, whose representatives denied that they had issued the invoices.
For example, counterfeiters did not notice that HIB s.r.o. from Nyíregyháza was in liquidation at the time (2001), when a group from fiatal Városért was eating there, which is why, according to our information, the company's liquidation commissioner also denied that he had published the paper.
Invoices were issued knowingly
The second group of invoicers consists of those who knew to issue a fictitious invoice.
The Eséla Budapestért Foundation has issued accounts for some four million forints to the Harmadik Évezredért Foundation at the request of Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták.
According to the indictment, the head of Collab s.r.o. was persuaded to issue a fictitious account by one of the accused, Ludovic Györfi.
Biogate s.r.o. also cooperated with Zuschlage and its partners, currently in liquidation, which in 2003 supplied the Jobb Jövőért Foundation and Atlasz and Vörösfenyő with invoices worth approximately five million forints for which there was no real economic activity.
Nor the movement of money, because the invoices created were later cancelled, which organizations forgot to mention in their documents.
Another group of billing firms includes those with ties to the defendants.
For example, Iván Kubatov was an authorized representative of the Ukrainian managing director of Delta Trió s.r.o., a fuel and motor vehicle trading company based in Budapest, but where the company is not found.
In October, November and December 2005, the company issued several invoices for the sale of computer equipment worth approximately 18 million forints.
According to the data collected by the investigation, these invoices were purchased by Kiskunhalas company Cash Investment s.r.o., which was liquidated from 14 September 2005.
The managing director of this company was a man from Romania, to whom Iván Kubatov was to be given documents relating to the company from 2002 to 2005.
As we know, Kubatov admitted during the investigation that he had issued invoices on behalf of the company to Atlasz, Hoppá and the Együtt and Harmadik Évezredért Foundations and had himself accepted their consideration.
At the request of Iván Kubatov, Fa-Bani Jos Faipari s.r.o. and Jos-Investment k. s. were founded by Romanian masons.
