He may have been offended, too, for his requests to relax the terms of his detention, namely the placement of house arrest, have so far been unansbeatable.
While the perpetrators of economic crimes who have done much more damage than they have not yet paid are free to walk, or at least wait for the end of the proceedings against them in their homes, he does not have this option.
The psychology of trumping: why are we spending more money?
In auctions, customers are willing to spend more money, overestimmute goods.
The neurological and economic foundations of this familiar - and seemingly irrational - behavior were revealed to researchers in the field of neurology and economics at New York University.
According to their study, published in the journal Science, people don't want to lag behind in a competition like the eBay auction, so they'd rather pay too high a price.
Using an experimental auction, the research tried to map a diagram of this "game" in the nervous system.
One group of volunteers bet, the other group participated in a staged auction, using the Functional Magnetic Resonance Imaging (fMRI) method to study the active areas of the brain of the test people.
In both games, participants could win money, but in an auction game, an important element of which is to trump the other side, the whole located under the cerebral cortex, called the striatum, began to function intensively during the losing.
This brain region plays a role in the "self-rewarding" mechanism of the nervous system, among many other functions.
According to the researchers, the unscrewing of the price can therefore be explained by trying to avoid a sharp reaction of the striatum.
To support their theory, members of the economists' research team conducted a financial cross-sectional survey.
Under different conditions, three groups auctioned against one partner.
The control group was simply told what the fair value of the product was and they made bets.
In addition, members of another group were promised that if they came out of the game victorious, they would receive an additional $15 as a reward.
The third group received $15 before the auction, but in the event of a loss, its members also lost the money.
So the difference between the two groups was that one was highlighted by winning and the other by losing.
However, members of the "against the loss" group were willing to go higher than in the control and "winning" group, confirming the neurologists' hypothesis.
"These results cannot be inferred from any pre-existing economic theory.
Until now, these have explained the phenomena observable in auctions of the joys of victory and risk avoidance.
It wasn't until neurological imaging methods that helped us resolve the contradiction between the two theories that we have now come to a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, a professor at New York University's School of Economics.
Hepatitis: when to see a doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infection, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is cited as one of the leading causes of death.
The number of domestic cases of hepatitis infection is estimated at 100,000, but only 7,000 of them are being treated. This is because the sick often do not know that they are infected.
The name hepatitis is the collective name of infectious liver damage caused by various viruses.
There are many similarities in their symptoms, symptoms are symptoms of inflammation of the liver and jaundice, but the agents of the disease and the diseases caused by them differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses spread in two main ways depending on the agents of the disease: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (for example, infected foods, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses through blood and body fluids (semen, vaginal secretions, saliva).
In any case, travellers should be protected by vaccination against A and B virus, there is no vaccine against type C virus.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after ingestion of infected food, usually accompanied by nausea, weakness, abdominal discomfort, urge to vomit.
Then jaundice is formed on the skin and eye whites, lightening the stool and darkening the urine. Treatment can take up to two to three weeks.
Every year, a million people worldwide die from a more serious type of this disease, liver cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main cause is that only one in ten people infected is estimated to be treated with medication.
Also, hepatitis C can have very serious consequences: if not treated, it can lead to liver cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, the causative agent of the disease destroys liver cells insidiously, so the first symptoms appear in many cases only in 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, the implementation of regular depressation is very important.
In three groups, this disease occurs much more often than on average: among people who had a blood transfusion before 1991, among drug users, and among people with tattoos.
Currently, the estimated worldwide number of individuals infected with chronic hepatitis C virus is 200 million.
Since the disease can already be demonstrated by a routine laboratory examination, a person should contact his general practitioner if he notices any symptom of unknown origin.
With early detection, the disease is treatable, the virus can be removed from the body to prevent contagiousness and prevent cancer.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, which was first organized worldwide in 2004 by organizations representing the sick.
Its aim is to draw attention to chronic inflammation of the liver caused by these viruses, the causes of its formation and the importance of early recognition of the disease.
Benelux governments national part of Fortis Bank
The Benelux states will help belgian-Dutch bank Fortis, which was the first in Europe to get into trouble because of the spreading effect of the US mortgage market crisis, by partially nationalization: the trio of countries will support the money and insurance institution, which also has a capital participation in Hungary, with €11.2 billion.
This was agreed at the highest level this weekend by the Belgian, Luxembourg and Dutch Governments, with the participation of the President of the European Central Bank and the European Commissioner for Competition.
Fortis is the first in the euro area to be in a major crisis in the international financial markets crisis, which has been spreading in waves for more than a year, and the decisions made on this issue could, in some respects, be seen as precedents.
In the sense of the decision, which was born on Sunday night, all three states will buy out almost half (49 percent) of the bank's assets there.
