Who believes in God doesn't hurt that much?
According to recent research, faith in God acts as a certain analgesic that could have facilitated death for already Catholic martyrs.
Scientists from the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment, examining how faith in the god affects the perception of pain in humans, the British daily Telegraph reported.
In a rather bizarre survey, 12 Catholic believers and an equal number of atheists were electrocuted, while all observed a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to rule out much of the pain.
Thanks to a technique that examines the human brain in detail, it has also been shown that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain that is responsible for regulating pain.
The research is the first in a series of research involving scientists, philosophers and theologians from different parts of the university, in addition to academics.
Exactly the test was carried out by attaching a sparkling instrument to the left hand of the test subject, which emitted electric shocks.
The researchers asked the participants in the experiment to stare at two paintings: Sassoferrat's Virgin Mary, dating from the 17th century, and Leonardo da Vinci's Lady with The Playfulness, painted in the 15th century.
The authors of the research hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary would evoke a certain state of piety among believers, while they chose da Vinci's painting because it is not very different from the first and seems reassuring.
The test subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, during which time they received 20 electroshogs in four consecutive parts, while separately watching a religious or general image.
Catholics reported feeling "safe" at the sight of the Virgin Mary, as if they had been "cared for" and "calmed down, filled with peace."
Watching a religious-themed painting, they said, they felt 12 percent less pain than when they had Leonardo's work in front of them.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the research, believes that a similar effect can be achieved with any strongly impressive image even in atheists, just the right photo needs to be found.
"We would have to find a picture that they would perceive very positively, from the position of mother or father," the psychologist said.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
"Practicing faith should change and, in many cases, change our personality," Wright added.
After such great results, it is only a question of what effect it would have on regulating the pain of believers if they were shown a madonna by Leonardo or a painter of similar caliber.
Would looking at a quality Virgin Mary mean achieving even better results?
You're what you share
On its 10th birthday, Google can claim that people can find it in their pocket at least as well as in the sky above their heads; they know where they were on holiday, what professional examinations they go to and what interests them.
But according to Eric Schmidt, one of the company's bosses, that's still not enough.
But when it comes to skeptics paralleling orwellian dark vision, the very nature of Web 2.0 is not clear to them.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google's main goal is to collect even more personal information about users, which is necessary for Google's founders to stick to their original goal, which was, "Let's organize all the information in the world!"
According to a Google official, after 10 years of world-class work, the company is only at the beginning of working with all the information.
When asked what would happen in five years, Schmidt replied that he would like Google to be able to answer questions like "what should I do tomorrow?" or "what kind of work would actually be right for me?" - but software won't be able to answer such seemingly simple questions until they know enough information about users.
Not all Internet users are well aware that during an internet search, the search words are accurately collected, as well as what IP address it was searched from and to which pages the searchers moved after the search.
For example, with Personalized Search launched two years ago, users can keep their surfing history, look back at what they've searched for and clicked on, generating findings that are much more directly tailored to them in the long run - the same logic will be used to create recommendations, through which the system will offer us products and services based on previously mentioned and retained preferences.
What if my data is used against me, what if someone looks at what I'm doing? - asks users who are afraid when looking at Google's data monopoly.
In most cases, the extent of the potential power represented by the company seems eerily threatening, the counter-reaction does not cause guilt in internet users, fear of punishment, a desire for freedom, or even a rebellion against power.
However, it is a confirmed fact that all search terms are not only recorded, but can also be issued to a third party in justified cases, in such legal cases the personal rights of Internet users do not protect anything.
Perhaps the most famous example of recent was the coordinated action against Brazilian pedophiles, during which Google provided the Brazilian government with information that allowed the identification of pedophiles from the Orkut community sites set up through it.
But internet users worried about personal rights could breathe a sigh of relief back in May when the company, in hand with the electronic rights organization EFF, successfully proved its truth in a dispute with the FBI: Google must not be forced to provide any information secretly requested by the FBI in the future.
(At the same time, the federal government successfully won nearly fifty thousand web addresses and thousands of search terms, which it obtained citing a strengthening of the Child Protection Act passed years ago, but still failed to get lists of individual users' search items, or complete lists of websites and keywords covering a period of two months.)
The view of Google is so contradictory: it is flogged by those who fear the disclosure of their personal data, because they feel that their intimate sphere and private life will be harmed by using Google's services, and they are speaking out against it with a revolt that belongs to multinational firms with a conservative image.
Meanwhile, American geek culture and its wild offshoot, grouping around enthusiastic computer fans, activists, and users, appearing in many countries, sees it as a new generation of big business, a "corporation that's now running," unlike its rival Microsoft, considered the conqueror of the world because of Windows, however much they both fight for the same goals.
This may be because Google, unlike Microsoft, does not require an identification code from its users and does not require money from them for its applications; an open, free and constantly fresh source of information and a package of programs feels much more accessible, youthful, "cooler" than the practice of an official software giant.
But it may also be because geeks understand precisely the very problematic relationship between the Internet and personality rights that has brought with it just one of the most glassy keywords of recent years: web 2.0.
Web 2.0 is about nothing more than cooperation, about deliberately leaving traces behind and using the communication channels at our disposal, and although their scope is different for everyone, the essence remains the same: we show up.
The average young person can profile on several community pages from Facebook to Xang, which they can easily link to other services, such as Twitter or the last.fm app, recording the music they listen to, all of which they can then connect to navigation systems such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm, in addition to writing a blog that automatically discovers their latest photo galleries , which he stores on Flickr or Picas.
In doing so, we can read about a lot of exemplary cases from which she can explain: in the morning, looking at a flood of photos of mutual friends, a friend easily finds out who her crazy boyfriend spent the evening with, or the company can fire its employee just because she will tell her honest opinion about the top management on her blog: one thing is certain, the concept of private life has been completely reconsidered today.
One who lives an online life consists of what he shows, so we could define the basic thesis behind the behavior of today's youth.
And anyone who wants to hide something, or at least avoid a Googling monopoly, has an option (starting with Scroogel, for example, who uses Google's search engine but deliberately leaves no trace).
For example, a significant number of people deliberately do not register on community sites to be found. Google's online applications, from text editor to photo editor and news portal, can be exchanged for alternative versions that are not connected to giant server parks and that do not build the highest quality profile possible.
Public opinion is not very secretly awaiting when Google will show its tooth.
With a current value of $156 billion, the business is worth more than IBM ($140 billion), Intel ($124 billion) or Coca Cola ($110 billion), AdWords/AdSense's advertising space threatens advertising agency investments, and services introduced at an ever-accelerating pace are seriously making life difficult not only for Microsoft, but also for numerous other software designers.
But critics also find counterpoints to the disturbing effect: the chief executive, for example, completely rejected employee protests after raising the company's kindergarten fee to twice that, arbitrarily frequent daily meals for employees were too expensive, according to the company's management, but all this is lost alongside the fact that Google bowed to the Chinese government in 2006 and, within the meaning of their agreement, filters out every finding. , which is against the good tastes or interests of the Chinese regime.
One of the company's internal rules is that it never advertises new services in advance, only when they can be used, but what is certain is that the expected problems of the coming months and years may be steering the world in new places: while some believe that Google's project to scan and archive books and magazines is taking on such dimensions that the company will soon have something to do with the US Supreme Court , others are terrified of her Health system, in which we can compile a complete health profile with previous findings, doctors and problems.
The fact that Google is compiling a genetic database can serve as a good starting point for future generations of science fiction writers, cory Doctorow's famous novel "Scroogled" describes with Orwellian reminiscences a future in which one can only get close to a person with google data.
