Smart car immitates bumblebee flight
What would be the best method of developing technologies capable of preventing collisions, if not imitations of obstacle detectors occurring in the world of nature?
For example, in bees.
Bumblebees inspired the initial strategic idea of the surprise project, presented at the CEATEC trade fair in Japan. It was about building a new generation of collision avoiding systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has designed the BR23C biomimetic robotic control system, a robotized minicar that features bee characteristics, with the ultimate goal of helping to create a system that can eliminate all collisions.
"During the flight, each bee creates its own personal space of an oval shape, which is actually very similar to our safety protective packaging," Kazuhiro Doi, the brand's general manager for technological PR and research and development, explained at the exhibition.
An important role is played by folded eyes, which allow bees to see in all directions at a viewing angle of more than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of the compound eye, the engineers reached for the idea of a laser range-range rangeometer.
It identifies obstacles up to 2 meters in front of the BR23C in a field of view of 180 degrees, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which instantly turns into an operation to prevent collision.
The obstacle is caught in a fraction of a second, then the robotized car begins to immit the movements of the bee and immediately changes direction by turning the wheels to the extent necessary to prevent collision.
Unlike any existing system, this switching maneuver takes place in a completely instinctive way.
"If this were not the case, the robotic car would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Ando, head of the Mobility Laboratory and robotic car project.
They must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology suits the most vulnerable and innermost layer of the safety protective packaging, inside which a collision is currently considered unavoidable.
The whole process must reflect what the bee does to avoid other bees.
This process must take no more than the blink of an eye.
However, unlike bees, this movement cannot be directed upwards, downwards or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and only in the direction in which the wheels can be rotated.
Instead of the endless possibilities offered to bees when avoiding, only the possibility of rotating movement, acceleration and deceleration was applied in the case of a robotic car.
BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and have a higher energy density, which means they have a longer lifespan than lithium-ion variants.
According to Ando, an instinctive, intelligent reaction is important, not the ability to process, much less the storage of data.
This mechanism must process and respond to only a few incoming signals per second.
There is no need for him to store and react using intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, therefore he constantly uses only memory the size of a few kilobytes.
It doesn't need giga- or megabyte memory.
This is the first step towards developing instant avoidance technology that Nissan estimates could reach mass-produced cars within a decade.
Another option may be to connect the unit to the GPS satellite navigation system, which, after avoiding obstacles, would lead the motorist to the specified final destination.
