The $700 billion economic rescue package bill, to be divided into several instalments and aimed at buying up low-quality bank loans, is already in writing.
Half of the amount will be used in the first round.
After further negotiations, which ended only after midnight U.S. Eastern Time on Saturday, congressional leaders reached an agreement in a days-long debate on a $700 billion bailout package, Reuters reported.
"We've made significant progress," said Nancy Pelosi, the Democratic leader of the House of Representatives, who said all that remains is to write an agreement.
Both presidential candidates, Barack Obama and John McCain, also supported the compromise on the package.
Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson said of the outcome of the compromise: "The programme will work and will be effective, but further action is needed."
The written version of the package was published before the opening of Asian markets at 8:00 p.m. Washington time on Sunday (2 a.m. Central European time Monday), but it did not cause any particular stock market rise.
The draft legislation, which will be adopted by the 2008 Emergency Economic Stabilization Act to establish the program, will be voted on first by the House of Representatives on Monday, then by the Senate.
President George W. Bush spoke with Pelosi on Saturday night, after news of the deal was also welcomed by the White House.
"We are pleased with the progress made last night and greatly appreciate both sides' efforts to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy," said White House spokesman Tony Fratto.
Indeed, the program differs from the Bush administration's original proposal to spend a total of $700 billion at a time to buy low-quality mortgage-backed securities.
It is now possible to spend no more than half of the $700 billion in the first round, so that $250 billion will be used immediately after Congress is expected to decide on the matter on Monday, and the Treasury Department will buy mortgage-backed securities that are rated as of poor quality, and the fate of the remaining $100 billion will depend on the president's decision.
The program will be controlled by a special body, of which the Chairman of the Federal Reserve Bank will also be a member.
Spending the second half of $700 billion will depend on another congressional decision.
The Ministry of Finance can apply a combined tactic within the meaning of the law: it can simultaneously buy low-quality loans, mortgages and mortgage-backed securities, or other "poisonous" loans.
The purchase can also take place directly within the framework of auctions, the competent representatives of the Ministry said.
The legislation will allow the companies concerned to participate in an insurance programme in which the Ministry of Finance grants them a guarantee for funds representing a cause for concern, for which the company will then pay a price corresponding to the amount of the expected damages.
As Henry Paulson said, the law provides the necessary resources to spend up to $700 billion to meet the urgent demands of the US financial system, whether it be large-scale purchases of bad funds, their insurance, or preventing systemic risk associated with the collapse of one of the big money institutions.
"We will take the necessary steps to be ready to introduce the law as soon as it is signed," he added.
On the contrary, bank bosses who have gotten into trouble and are waiting for state help can count on the government to reduce their severance pay - which in overseas slang is simply called a "golden parachute."
Their payouts will be restricted only in certain cases, in addition, these restrictions will depend on the method of assistance provided by the Ministry.
The restriction essentially means that if the Ministry buys as part of an auction, a tax surchar down on gold parachutes will be imposed unless fallen bank directors are sent straight into retirement.
In the case of direct purchases of poor-quality loans, the government will aggressively act to ensure that the money for management is not excessive.
It should be added that the existing contracts for gold falls will not change, the restriction applies only to new contracts, which is intended to be a further incentive to participate in the programme.
"This is the first time in American history that a legal limitation on ceo pay will be in place," said Barney Frank, chairman of the House Financial Services Committee.
Moreover, the state will have the right to acquire a stake in the banks participating in the programme, thereby reducing the risk to taxpayers, since once the economy and the rescued bank get back on their feet, they can also profit from the transaction.
The bill includes that over the next five years, the president must submit a proposal to Congress setting out how expected losses from the financial sector can be returned to taxpayers.
Of course, there were also voices on both sides expressing doubts about the plan.
"That's not what the American people have been ask of us, because that's not going to protect taxpayer dollars," said Republican Congressman Darrell Issa of California.
His Democratic colleague from Ohio, Mary Kaptur, resents that the provisions were pushed by those responsible for wall street's collapse.
Industrial prices continued to rise
Domestic sales prices in industry increased by 0.1 percent in August 2008 compared to the previous month, and by 12.9 percent compared to August 2007, the Central Statistical Office reported.
Export sales prices in industry were higher by 1.1 percent compared to July 2008, down 3.9 percent year-on-year.
As a result of changes in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices were higher by 0.7 percent compared to the previous month, up 3.2 percent year-on-year.
Domestic sales prices in the industry rose only minimally, by 0.1 percent compared to the previous month.
Domestic sales prices in the manufacturing sector also increased slightly, by 0.1 percent compared to July.
The largest price increase took place in August 2008 in the leather and footwear industry (2.8 percent), mainly due to a monthly price increase of 4.6 percent in the bag and saddlery industry and 2.5 percent in footwear production, respectively.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical raw materials caused a significant monthly increase in prices in the chemicals and products production sector (1.6 percent).
Prices fell in the oil processing sector (1.4 percent), production of electrical machinery and equipment (0.9 percent), as well as - to a minimum - in the woodworking sector (0.1 percent).
Prices in the paper production and publishing and printing business remained unchanged.
In other manufacturing sectors, we measured price increases in the range of 0.2 - 0.9 percent.
In the electricity, gas and water generation and distribution sector, which is of great importance in domestic sales of the industry, prices rose by 0.3 percent in August, mainly due to the continued impact of the officially established increase in gas prices since July 1.
In a 12-month comparison of domestic sales in the various sectors of the manufacturing industry, prices rose the most in the professional oil processing sector (32.4 percent).
In the metalworking sector, a 13.2% increase in prices could be observed, and an 11% increase in prices in the production of food products, beverages and tobacco products, which is crucial.
Prices decreased in the textile and textile production sectors (2.5 percent) and in the production of electrical machinery and equipment (0.3 percent).
In other manufacturing sectors, the rate of price growth ranged between 0.6 and 9.1 percent.
Overall, prices in the manufacturing sector have risen by 10.2 percent over the past year.
Prices in the electricity, gas and water generation and distribution sectors exceeded previous year's prices by 18.7 percent.
In terms of sector-by-sector division, domestic sales in August showed the highest monthly price increase (0.7 percent) in the tangible asset production sectors.
Prices rose by 0.3 percent in consumer goods industries, while prices in energy processing and further processing sectors remained unchanged from the previous month.
The largest price increases in August 2008 compared to the same month of the previous year could be observed in energy processing and further processing sectors (16,8 percent).
In the consumer goods industries, we measured a price increase of 6.8 percent, while for tangible assets, a price decrease of 1.4 percent.
Export sales prices of industrial products measured in forints increased by 1.1 percent in August compared to the previous month, down 3.9 percent in the 12-month comparison.
Our domestic currency weakened by 1.7 percent against the euro in one month, then by 7.1 percent against the dollar, up 7.5 percent against the euro and 15.9 percent against the dollar.
