Fox in the chicken coop
Life and health insurance companies in America often reject the possibility of signing an insurance contract with a candidate based on people's data on drug purchases.
Data protection experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
'There is a data protection programme which binds the use of prescription data in any case to the authorisation of the person concerned.
It has to be in the hands of someone independent, otherwise we entrust the chicken coop to a fox," the Washington Post quotes Richard Dick, author of a program designed to monitor prescriptions.
Insurance companies make premiums and amounts paid in the event of claims dependent on the health status of candidates and, if the risk is assessed as too great, they will not even take out insurance with it.
Previously, they sent the people for medical examinations and only contracted when they knew their results.
Ten years ago, Dick devised a much cheaper procedure: based on the identification number, the customer easily finds out from pharmacies what drugs the person has bought in the last year and a half, from which the program itself infers what disease it suffers from and what its state of health is.
For example, if he regularly buys a large amount of cholesterol lowering drugs, it refers to the fact that he has virtually uncontrollably high blood fat levels, which immediately put him in a category with a higher risk.
There are several versions of the program in circulation, some of which also determine the risk factor, so that the insurance company has almost no work left besides paperwork, although minor difficulties arise.
Among the disadvantages is that some drugs can be used for several purposes, some compounds are, for example, usable against migraine or hot flashes, but they are also effective against depression.
These represent an important risk-increasing factor from the point of view of commercial insurance companies, whereas the former do not.
In order to request and process the data, special companies have been set up to ask the patient's permission before they can obtain the necessary information from pharmacies.
They are now being forced to do so by the authorities, even if they have not been punished for their negligence so far.
Recently, some companies have been processing the results of laboratory examinations, which they combine with data on the medicines used, thanks to which they are able to provide an even more accurate picture of the health of patients.
More and more companies have access to the data, while controlling their use will become increasingly difficult.
There is a special health data protection law, but its effectiveness applies only to health service providers and insurance companies.
The bill, which will give authorities the power to control even businesses specializing in data provision, is before Congress.
Richard Dick acknowledges that this is not enough: that is why he has developed his programme so that the transfer of data is linked to the explicit consent of the person concerned.
Another thing is that it can hardly deny the permission in question, otherwise the insurance companies will not conclude a contract with it.
So the hens are somewhat reliated on fox's goodwill after all.
