Elites in danger
This phenomenon emerged a few days ago, when the House of Representatives voted against a $700 billion rescue plan put forward by the White House: a significant portion of Americans were more interested in punishing Wall Street than in saving the economy.
This is confirmed by yesterday's New York Times, which informs us that the current crisis is tearing the Republican Party apart, increasingly divided between its old East Coast soul, softer, welcoming to federal institutions and the business community, and its new soul, which, on the contrary, is conservative, hostile to "those in Washington" and to the world of finance, strong especially in the states of the middle and south.
A soul that has arrogantly manifested itself in the vote I was talking about at the beginning.
But this just-cited thing is merely an example of the changes, big changes that the current economic earthquake is already showing : not only in the United States, but throughout the West, and perhaps not just here.
Both in America and In Europe, this crisis seems to act as an accelerator of the events that have long been incubated, which are tightening in the new climate and finally coming to light.
The first of these events is the re-edification, the extraordinary recovery of the market, the double category state-power in relation to a certain re-nationalization of economics.
Indeed, the crisis is a crisis for financial institutions, which, of course, have strong ties abroad, but which primarily include the budgets of people and families living in a single country, a single state, to the greatest extent.
This has also created a political problem for those who run it: that is, how to respond to the difficulties and protests of people and families who are, among other things, voters.
In short, the crisis seems economically global, but politically almost entirely national.
Political internationality seems to be substantially out of the question, or that it has little to add: the obvious evidence has been given by the European Union, which, as always, is divided between different interests and different national strategies, and which cannot opt for one common political line.
And so everyone expects the intervention of the government of each individual state, rescue plans, market recovery, new rules and, above all, the distribution of funds: at the moment we get into a state of crisis, only states have the economic resources, the amount of financial resources to be able to try to put everything right.
And they also possess the necessary means and authorisations to use them: two sources of immense value, in certain circumstances that perhaps no market and no international organisation will ever be able to possess to a similar extent.
Moreover, this new emphasis, which the crisis places on a state-national element, is in full compliance with the increasing importance that the latest economic advances are trying to attribute to one factor closely linked to it: territorial jurisdiction.
Paradoxically, while we were convinced that we had entered the kingdom of the sita, increasingly sophisticated technology, immaterial, while we were convinced that global finance was already destined to rule the world, all of a sudden we realised that our future would have to deal with little intangent things like water, grain, diesel.
All things that would have been said can be transported from one place on earth to another, but they are in any case connected, absolutely, to a bounded space, territory.
So, whoever becomes their ruler certainly has a lot more cards up their sleeve than who isn't, and who's unlucky enough to live in a place without grain, without oil, and without water.
I come to the second novelty, which, however, foreseses a turning point.
Those who talk about territory, state, government inevitably talk about politics, that is, leadership.
Taking into account the economic crisis, two convergent phenomena appear to be forming.
On the one hand, the realization that there is an objective need for authoritarian leadership, a request for someone who can seize the situation.
